The '''Wakatobi white-eye''' ('''''Zosterops flavissimus''''') is a [[species]] of [[bird]] in the family [[White-eye|Zosteropidae]]. It is [[Endemism|endemic]] to Indonesia, where it is known only from the [[Wakatobi Regency|Wakatobi Islands]] off south-eastern [[Sulawesi]]. It can be distinguished from most other Indonesian white-eyes by its bright yellow belly. It was formerly considered a subspecies of the [[lemon-bellied white-eye]] (''Z. chloris''), but it was long known to be reproductively isolated from the rest of the species, and a 2019 genetic study found it to be a distinct species.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Marples|first=Nicola M.|last2=Analuddin|first2=Kangkuso|last3=Karya|first3=Adi|last4=Marcaigh|first4=Fionn Ó|last5=O’Brien|first5=Katie|last6=Lawless|first6=Naomi|last7=Kelly|first7=David J.|last8=O’Connell|first8=Darren P.|title=A sympatric pair of undescribed white-eye species (Aves: Zosteropidae: Zosterops) with different origins|journal=Zoological Journal of the Linnean Society|volume=186|issue=3|pages=701–724|language=en|doi=10.1093/zoolinnean/zlz022|year=2019|doi-access=free}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sci-news.com/biology/wakatobi-wangi-wangi-white-eyes-07125.html|title=Two New Species of White-Eyes Discovered in Indonesia {{!}} Biology {{!}} Sci-News.com|website=Breaking Science News {{!}} Sci-News.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-09}}</ref>

